'''Ecosemiotics''' is a branch of [[semiotics]] in its intersection with [[human ecology]] that studies the sign relations established by culture, which deal with other living beings, communities, and landscapes.<ref>Farina, Almo; Santolini, Riccardo; Pagliaro, Giacomo; Scozzafava, Silvia; Schipani, Ileana 2005. Ecosemiotics: A new field of competence for ecology to overcome the frontier between environmental complexity and human culture in the Mediterranean. ''Israel Journal of Plant Sciences'' 53(3/4): 167–175.</ref>
The field was initiated by [[Winfried Nöth]] and [[Kalevi Kull]].<ref>*Maran, Timo 2007. Towards an integrated methodology of ecosemiotics: The concept of nature-text. ''Sign Systems Studies'' 35(1/2): 269–294.</ref>
The central focus of ecosemiotics concerns the role of concepts (sign-based models people have) in designing and changing the environment. Ecosemiotics includes (or largely overlaps) with semiotics of landscape.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/11557974/Landscape_semiotics Lindström, Kati; Kull, Kalevi; Palang, Hannes 2014. Landscape semiotics: Contribution to culture theory.] In: Lang, Valter; Kull, Kalevi (eds.), ''Estonian Approaches to Culture Theory''. Tartu: University of Tartu Press, 110–132.</ref>
==See also== *[[Biosemiotics]] *[[Ecolinguistics]]
==Literature== *[[Winfried Nöth|Nöth, Winfried]] 1998. Ecosemiotics. ''[[Sign Systems Studies]]'' 26: 332–343. *[[Kalevi Kull|Kull, Kalevi]] 1998. Semiotic ecology: Different natures in the semiosphere. ''Sign Systems Studies'' 26: 344–371.[https://www.academia.edu/6016834/Semiotic_ecology_different_natures_in_the_semiosphere] *Maran, Timo; Kull, Kalevi 2014. Ecosemiotics: main principles and current developments. ''Geografiska Annaler: Series B, Human Geography'' 96(1): 41–50.[https://www.academia.edu/6608956/Maran_and_Kull_-_Ecosemiotics_main_principles_and_current_developments]
