The '''Golden Banana''' or "sun belt" is a term used by analysts when discussing [[urbanisation]] in a European context.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}} It denotes an area of higher population density lying between [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]] in the west and [[Genoa]] in the east along the coast of the [[Mediterranean Sea]], defined by the "Europe 2000" report from the European Commission in 1995{{citation needed|date=February 2015}} to be analogous to the [[Blue Banana]]. The region is a centre for [[information technology]] and [[manufacturing]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eskelinen|first1=Heikki|last2=Liikanen|first2=Ilkka|last3=Oska|first3=Jukka|title=Curtains of iron and gold: reconstructing borders and scales of interaction|year=1999|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=1-84014-460-2|page=119}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oenb.at/de/img/ws_09_tcm14-42773.pdf |title=New Regional Economics in Central European Economies: The Future of CENTROPE |date=March 2006 |work=Proceedings of OeNB Workshops |accessdate=22 August 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926205501/http://www.oenb.at/de/img/ws_09_tcm14-42773.pdf |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df= }}</ref>

