{{about|the 19th-century engineer|his grandson and the 20th-century author|Nils Johan Schjander (1931–2009)}}

'''Nils Johan Schjander''' (1859–1903) was a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] engineer and a member of the movement known as the [[Kristiania Bohemians]].<ref>Stubhaug, Arild. 2013. ''The Mathematician Sophus Lie: It Was the Audacity of My Thinking''. Transl. Richard H. Daly. Berlin: Springer, p. 484.</ref> He is known for having taken part in a journey to [[Patagonia]] and writing a diary, published as ''En reise til Patagonia'' (A Journey to Patagonia).<ref>Schjander, Nils Johan. 2000. ''En reise til Patagonia''. Oslo : Forlaget Press.</ref> For the Kristiania Bohemians, Patagonia was a promised land where several dreamed of creating a free state.<ref>Bing, Jon. 1980. ''Fra Maurits C. Hansen til Arne Garborg''. Oslo: Gyldendal, p. 184.</ref> Schjander was involved in surveying and mapping Patagonia on behalf of the Argentine Southern Land Company between 1889 and 1891.<ref>[http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/2000/11/26/229880.html Mosnes, Terje. 2000. Bohemen som dro til Patagonia. ''Dagbladet'' (November 26).]</ref>

